WEBVTT

00:03.334 --> 00:05.601
No way, Claud, 20's too many.
You gotta cut it down.

00:05.601 --> 00:06.734
Cut what down?

00:06.734 --> 00:07.901
What are we
talking about?

00:07.901 --> 00:09.934
P-A-R-T-Y list.

00:09.934 --> 00:10.934
What party?

00:10.934 --> 00:12.000
Yeah, what party?

00:12.000 --> 00:13.434
Bailey.

00:13.434 --> 00:15.200
He said "potty," O.

00:15.200 --> 00:16.801
B-I-R-T-H-D-A-Y,

00:16.801 --> 00:18.033
this Saturday.

00:18.033 --> 00:19.801
Oh, right.

00:19.801 --> 00:21.133
Man, I totally forgot.

00:21.133 --> 00:23.734
I'm stunned.
CHARLIE: Is it too much to ask

00:23.734 --> 00:25.801
that we have
an attitude-free dinner?

00:25.801 --> 00:27.367
Whatever you want.
You're the boss.

00:27.367 --> 00:29.534
Okay, okay.
How is tomorrow for everyone?

00:29.534 --> 00:30.901
For what?

00:30.901 --> 00:33.834
Duh, P-A-R-T-Y's don't just
plan themselves, you know.

00:33.834 --> 00:35.300
I mean, first a C-A-K-E,

00:35.300 --> 00:36.601
and the bakery's next to a store

00:36.601 --> 00:38.701
where we can get the T-O-Y's
and stuff.

00:38.701 --> 00:41.000
Are you thinking we're
gonna all do this together?

00:41.000 --> 00:42.367
Yeah. It'll be fun.

00:42.367 --> 00:44.634
It'll be like
a-a family project.

00:44.634 --> 00:47.734
But we have to be back by 3:00
to interview the C-L-O-W-N.

00:47.734 --> 00:50.234
We have to interview the clown?

00:50.234 --> 00:51.400
Julia. Ugh.

00:52.667 --> 00:53.901
S-O-R-R-Y.

00:53.901 --> 00:55.200
Grace has her day off tomorrow.

00:55.200 --> 00:56.701
I told her we'd spend it
together.

00:56.701 --> 00:58.667
Why don't we just
divvy up the jobs

00:58.667 --> 00:59.934
and do 'em all
on our own time?

00:59.934 --> 01:02.133
I'm all over that.
No, no, no, no.

01:02.133 --> 01:04.667
See, the point was for us
to do this together.

01:04.667 --> 01:06.667
I'll do the C-A-K-E.

01:06.667 --> 01:08.567
I'll take the T-O-Y's
and stuff.

01:08.567 --> 01:11.701
That leaves you the C-L-O-W-N.

01:11.701 --> 01:13.868
JULIA: That's fitting.
BAILEY: Shut up, Julia.

01:13.868 --> 01:16.167
Here.

01:16.167 --> 01:17.767
What's your problem?

01:19.167 --> 01:20.534
I just--

01:20.534 --> 01:23.767
I wanted us all to do something
fun together for a change.

01:26.567 --> 01:28.601
What do you call this?

01:28.601 --> 01:33.701
 <i>[THE BODEANS' "CLOSER TO FIVE"</i>
 <i>PLAYING]</i>

01:33.701 --> 01:36.467
 <i>* Everybody wants to live *</i>

01:36.467 --> 01:38.467
 <i>* Like they wanna live *</i>

01:38.467 --> 01:41.834
 <i>* And everybody wants to love *</i>

01:41.834 --> 01:43.400
 <i>* Like they wanna love *</i>

01:43.400 --> 01:47.367
 <i>* Everybody wants to be *</i>

01:47.367 --> 01:52.234
 <i>* Closer to free-ee-ee-ee *</i>

01:52.234 --> 01:55.133
 <i>* Closer to free *</i>

01:59.534 --> 02:03.767
[MACHINERY BUZZING,
ROCK MUSIC PLAYING OVER STEREO]

02:03.767 --> 02:05.701
You know how
in Henry James novels

02:05.701 --> 02:10.167
when a character hits maturity,
he takes a grand tour of Europe?

02:10.167 --> 02:11.400
No.

02:11.400 --> 02:12.901
But I'll take your word for it.

02:12.901 --> 02:15.167
Well, I've been trying
to figure out what I'm gonna do

02:15.167 --> 02:17.601
after I graduate,
and I think--

02:17.601 --> 02:20.901
Well, I think
I'm gonna do that.

02:20.901 --> 02:22.434
You're gonna take
a grand tour?

02:22.434 --> 02:24.400
Well, more like a baby grand.

02:24.400 --> 02:26.868
I'm gonna buy a backpack
and a Eurail pass

02:26.868 --> 02:29.801
and travel till
my money runs out.

02:29.801 --> 02:31.667
How long is that?

02:31.667 --> 02:32.734
I don't know.

02:32.734 --> 02:34.968
No more than 3 months.

02:36.534 --> 02:38.100
What? Wait.

02:38.100 --> 02:40.534
What about the stuff
that we were gonna do together

02:40.534 --> 02:42.100
this summer?

02:42.100 --> 02:43.267
What stuff?

02:43.267 --> 02:45.501
Have we talked about
doing stuff?

02:45.501 --> 02:48.767
 Well, no, not--
Not, like, verbally,

02:48.767 --> 02:50.400
but that doesn't mean...

02:52.234 --> 02:54.067
Man, three months without you.
That, um...

02:56.267 --> 02:57.801
You know what?

02:57.801 --> 02:59.701
You should come.

02:59.701 --> 03:00.868
[LAUGHS]
What?

03:00.868 --> 03:01.868
To Europe?

03:01.868 --> 03:03.667
Yeah.
With you?

03:03.667 --> 03:05.400
Yeah, it's a great idea.

03:05.400 --> 03:07.901
You, me, cafÃ©s, beaches.

03:07.901 --> 03:10.334
Oh, Jule, uh--
Look, I-- I would love to,

03:10.334 --> 03:12.601
but this is a huge remodel
I just started.

03:12.601 --> 03:15.834
Oh, come on, remodel shmemodel.

03:15.834 --> 03:19.968
Did you know there
is a bridge in Venice,

03:19.968 --> 03:23.100
if you kiss underneath it,
your love lasts forever?

03:27.767 --> 03:28.834
[LAUGHS]

03:30.200 --> 03:31.734
When did you wanna go?

03:32.601 --> 03:33.534
[GIGGLES]

03:37.601 --> 03:41.634
Excuse me, I-- I'm looking for,
uh, sing-along tapes for kids.

03:41.634 --> 03:43.667
Anything but Barney.

03:43.667 --> 03:46.334
Ooh, Barney backlash.

03:47.767 --> 03:50.267
Thanks.
If those tapes are for you,

03:50.267 --> 03:52.934
I am going to kill myself.

03:52.934 --> 03:54.434
[CLAUDIA LAUGHS,
AVERY GRUNTS]

03:54.434 --> 03:56.901
Avery, hi.

03:56.901 --> 03:59.968
A birthday present
for my little brother.

03:59.968 --> 04:01.567
This is for me.

04:01.567 --> 04:02.934
Uh-huh. Uh-huh.

04:02.934 --> 04:05.033
Oh, the Grieg.

04:05.033 --> 04:08.701
Oh, yes, yes.
You will do very well with this.

04:08.701 --> 04:09.834
You think?

04:09.834 --> 04:11.667
Yes, I do.

04:11.667 --> 04:13.267
But I'll tell you what.
Don't buy it.

04:13.267 --> 04:15.067
I will loan you my copy.

04:15.067 --> 04:16.601
Really?
Mm-hm.

04:16.601 --> 04:19.166
Wow, great. Thanks.

04:19.166 --> 04:22.200
Maybe-- Maybe I could come
pick it up right now.

04:22.200 --> 04:25.100
You know, we could hang out.
Catch up.

04:25.100 --> 04:27.033
Oh, I would love to.

04:27.033 --> 04:30.400
But I'm actually spending
the afternoon with my son.

04:30.400 --> 04:33.100
Wait. You have a son?

04:33.100 --> 04:34.167
I never knew that.

04:34.167 --> 04:36.367
Well, I thought I-- Yeah.

04:36.367 --> 04:38.634
Well-- Yeah, yeah. Marcus.

04:38.634 --> 04:40.567
He's 14.

04:40.567 --> 04:43.300
He was living in L.A.
with his mother.

04:43.300 --> 04:46.367
And, well, things weren't
working out, so...

04:46.367 --> 04:47.734
Really?

04:47.734 --> 04:50.534
So, I mean, did he just get up
here, like-- Like recently?

04:50.534 --> 04:52.567
Well, a month ago.

04:52.567 --> 04:54.167
He's still settling in.

04:54.167 --> 04:56.133
Why don't--?
Why don't I show him around?

04:56.133 --> 04:57.434
I've lived here my whole life.

04:57.434 --> 04:59.400
I know all
the cool stuff to do.

04:59.400 --> 05:01.000
You don't have do that.

05:01.000 --> 05:02.534
No, no, no, no.
I want to. I mean it.

05:02.534 --> 05:03.567
I mean, I think it'd be fun.

05:05.534 --> 05:07.267
I would be
an excellent tour guide.

05:07.267 --> 05:09.534
All right, you're hired.

05:09.534 --> 05:11.834
[LAUGHS]

05:11.834 --> 05:14.734
Explain to me the logic of going
all the way up a mountain

05:14.734 --> 05:17.033
and then turning around
and coming right back down.

05:17.033 --> 05:18.801
That's what
hiking is, Charlie.

05:18.801 --> 05:19.901
[LAUGHS]

05:21.367 --> 05:22.701
CHARLIE:
Hey, Bay.

05:22.701 --> 05:24.200
Taking out a loan?

05:24.200 --> 05:28.601
No. I need C-A-S-H
for the C-L-O-W-N.

05:28.601 --> 05:30.033
Gotta get to the bank.

05:30.033 --> 05:32.834
Oh, um, Grace's parents called.

05:32.834 --> 05:34.467
They said
they were in the area,

05:34.467 --> 05:36.467
and they wanna take you guys
to dinner tonight.

05:36.467 --> 05:38.100
CHARLIE: Oh, great.
GRACE: What?

05:38.100 --> 05:41.000
Yeah. Call them at your sister's
to tell them when and where.

05:41.000 --> 05:42.300
Oh, my God.
CHARLIE: Wait,

05:42.300 --> 05:43.968
I'm supposed
to have Owen tonight.

05:43.968 --> 05:46.400
I need you to cover.
What about Julia?

05:46.400 --> 05:48.868
Julia doesn't owe me. You do.

05:48.868 --> 05:51.100
No, Bailey.
It's okay, really.

05:51.100 --> 05:54.501
Well, I am behind
in a couple classes.

05:54.501 --> 05:57.000
Probably do me good to stay in.
So when? 7?

05:57.734 --> 05:59.734
Cool.
Cool.

06:02.167 --> 06:04.601
Not cool, Charlie,
not cool at all.

06:04.601 --> 06:05.801
[CHUCKLES]

06:05.801 --> 06:07.868
What's the problem?
This will be fun.

06:07.868 --> 06:11.667
Wow, I really haven't given you
a clear picture of them, have I?

06:11.667 --> 06:14.834
Nothing I've done since I
decided not to go to law school,

06:14.834 --> 06:16.701
nothing has been acceptable
to them.

06:16.701 --> 06:19.667
Not my jobs, not my apartments,
and certainly not my boyfriends.

06:19.667 --> 06:22.267
Maybe they were
right about that.

06:22.267 --> 06:25.801
Maybe everyone before me
was a great big loser.

06:25.801 --> 06:27.100
Don't take their side.

06:27.100 --> 06:28.200
[CHUCKLES]

06:28.200 --> 06:30.167
Okay.

06:30.167 --> 06:32.300
Parents in,
sense of humor out.

06:32.300 --> 06:34.501
I'm sorry.
It's-- It's just--

06:34.501 --> 06:35.934
It's gonna be a nightmare.

06:35.934 --> 06:37.200
Well, maybe not.

06:37.200 --> 06:39.234
Maybe they just wanna see
what kind of guy I am.

06:39.234 --> 06:42.467
They already know. The Not-Good-
Enough-For-Their-Daughter kind.

06:42.467 --> 06:43.901
[SIGHS]

06:44.934 --> 06:46.801
[DOOR OPENS, KEYS JINGLING]

06:46.801 --> 06:49.033
Marcus, hup-hup!

06:49.033 --> 06:51.267
I have a friend
I would like you to meet.

06:51.267 --> 06:53.133
Claudia,
this is my son Marcus.

06:53.133 --> 06:54.701
Hi.

06:54.701 --> 06:56.033
Hey.

06:56.033 --> 06:57.534
I'll be right back.

06:59.567 --> 07:01.868
So, Marcus...

07:01.868 --> 07:04.133
What school are you in?
It's Mark.

07:04.133 --> 07:06.100
Oh, I-- I thought he said--

07:06.100 --> 07:08.367
He's the only one
that calls me that.

07:12.734 --> 07:14.834
How do you know him, anyway?

07:14.834 --> 07:17.567
I play the violin,

07:17.567 --> 07:20.434
so through that, kind of.

07:20.434 --> 07:21.567
Do you play anything?

07:21.567 --> 07:23.234
Basketball.

07:23.234 --> 07:26.000
But I got up here
in the middle of the season.

07:26.000 --> 07:28.734
I meant music.

07:28.734 --> 07:29.868
An instrument?

07:30.434 --> 07:31.534
Oh.

07:32.501 --> 07:34.434
No.

07:38.467 --> 07:39.767
Do you wanna watch videos?

07:41.167 --> 07:42.267
Sure.

07:47.167 --> 07:48.767
[MARCUS SIGHS]

07:48.767 --> 07:52.000
[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING OVER TV]

07:54.000 --> 07:56.234
Oh, why don't we
turn that off, hm?

07:56.234 --> 07:57.868
It's not to Claudia's taste.

07:57.868 --> 08:00.400
Oh, no. It's okay.

08:00.400 --> 08:01.968
[MUSIC STOPS]

08:01.968 --> 08:04.467
And while I'm thinking of it,
why don't I get you that Grieg?

08:04.467 --> 08:05.601
It's around here somewhere.

08:13.067 --> 08:16.300
Is this--?
Wh-where is this from?

08:16.300 --> 08:17.801
AVERY:
Well, that's the first time

08:17.801 --> 08:19.734
that your mother and I
played in New York.

08:19.734 --> 08:22.467
Wow, look--
Look how young you both were.

08:22.467 --> 08:25.033
Mm, yeah, actually, I have
a recording of that concert.

08:25.033 --> 08:26.467
Would you like to hear it?

08:26.467 --> 08:27.567
Are you kidding?

08:27.567 --> 08:28.767
Sure.

08:28.767 --> 08:30.868
All right, great. It's in here.

08:34.067 --> 08:36.933
[SIGHS]

08:36.933 --> 08:38.333
 <i>[ROCK MUSIC PLAYING]</i>

08:41.701 --> 08:44.801
OWEN: Bam!
Oh, God, Owen.

08:46.000 --> 08:47.234
I'm sorry.

08:47.234 --> 08:49.534
He's usually so well-behaved
in restaurants.

08:49.534 --> 08:51.667
Must be way past his bedtime.
[OWEN SHOUTING]

08:51.667 --> 08:53.701
Uh, do you want a little pie,
Owen?

08:53.701 --> 08:54.634
No.

08:56.567 --> 08:59.734
So, um, back to your
Russian trip.

08:59.734 --> 09:00.934
What were we talking about?

09:00.934 --> 09:04.033
Uh, goulash, was it?
Let go. Put me down.

09:04.033 --> 09:06.434
Ha-ha! Gulags.
Soviet political prisons.

09:06.434 --> 09:07.534
[CHUCKLES]

09:07.534 --> 09:09.400
Of course. Heh-heh!

09:09.400 --> 09:11.801
MARTIN:
They usually don't let you
anywhere near them.

09:11.801 --> 09:14.234
But this fellow I knew
back in D.C. is in the Embassy.

09:14.234 --> 09:15.567
Excuse me, excuse me.

09:15.567 --> 09:17.067
Louie, did Bailey
call back yet?

09:17.067 --> 09:18.200
Uh, nope, not yet.

09:18.200 --> 09:19.901
OWEN: I'm tired.

09:19.901 --> 09:21.734
I'm sorry, go on.

09:21.734 --> 09:23.901
Is that like him
to not show up?

09:23.901 --> 09:27.601
No, no. He's usually-- Heh-heh.
--very reliable.

09:27.601 --> 09:30.100
But, uh, I don't know.
I'm sure there's nothing--

09:30.100 --> 09:31.367
I'm-- I'm sure he's fine.

09:31.367 --> 09:34.133
Ow! Owen, God.
I wanna go home.

09:34.133 --> 09:36.133
Well, just sit tight,
all right?

09:36.133 --> 09:37.968
He seems really tired, Charlie.

09:37.968 --> 09:40.067
CHARLIE: No, he'll--
I wanna go home.

09:40.067 --> 09:41.801
He'll settle down here
in a minute.

09:41.801 --> 09:44.767
Maybe we should save this story
for another time.

09:44.767 --> 09:46.801
Uh, waiter?
Could we have the check, please?

09:46.801 --> 09:49.234
No, Martin, this is--
This is on the house.

09:49.234 --> 09:50.801
Oh, no. Mm-mm.
OWEN: Wanna go home.

09:50.801 --> 09:53.767
I know how rough
the restaurant business is.

09:53.767 --> 09:56.501
I won't have you going belly-up
because of me.

09:56.501 --> 09:59.200
[BANGING]

10:02.234 --> 10:05.834
[DOOR OPENS THEN CLOSES]

10:05.834 --> 10:07.767
CHARLIE:
Now, go put your p.j.'s on,
okay, O?

10:09.167 --> 10:11.200
[SIGHS]

10:11.200 --> 10:12.834
Bailey call?

10:12.834 --> 10:13.934
No.

10:16.067 --> 10:18.033
[PHONE DIALING]

10:19.334 --> 10:21.267
What you looking up?
 <i>[PHONE RINGING]</i>

10:21.267 --> 10:24.067
France, Italy, Spain, Greece.

10:24.767 --> 10:26.133
Term paper?

10:26.133 --> 10:29.334
Mm-mm. A graduation present
for myself, a trip to Europe.

10:30.634 --> 10:31.868
Great idea.

10:33.901 --> 10:35.033
Damn.

10:37.167 --> 10:39.000
So who you gonna go with, Sarah?

10:42.100 --> 10:44.100
Oh, no way.

10:44.100 --> 10:45.501
I don't wanna hear it.

10:45.501 --> 10:48.000
Hey, guys, want some tea?
I'm boiling water.

10:48.000 --> 10:50.200
Julia's going to Europe
with Sam.

10:50.200 --> 10:52.400
You're kidding.
No.

10:52.400 --> 10:54.467
Why is that so unbelievable?

10:54.467 --> 10:56.567
You mean, aside
from the fact that he's 24

10:56.567 --> 10:58.167
and you're a minor?

10:58.167 --> 11:01.400
That's actually illegal,
isn't it?
I'll be 18 by then.

11:01.400 --> 11:03.200
And why are you even
in this conversation?

11:03.200 --> 11:05.167
You're not a member
of this family.

11:05.167 --> 11:06.834
Look, Charlie
addressed me, so--

11:06.834 --> 11:09.234
Well, he shouldn't have.
My plans are not your business.

11:09.234 --> 11:11.334
You know what, Charlie? They
aren't yours either.

11:11.334 --> 11:13.234
[KETTLE WHISTLING]

11:14.667 --> 11:16.601
[RINGING]
[LAUGHTER]

11:19.801 --> 11:21.667
BOY: You got your brewskies...?
Yeah?

11:21.667 --> 11:23.300
Oh, hi, Charlie.

11:23.300 --> 11:25.434
Uh, no, uh-uh. He's not.
[BOTTLES CLINKING]

11:25.434 --> 11:27.033
Hey, could you grab me one?

11:28.133 --> 11:29.467
Um, yeah, sure.

11:29.467 --> 11:31.767
I'll tell him, but, uh,
it might be kinda late, though.

11:31.767 --> 11:33.767
'Cause I just left him
at this party,

11:33.767 --> 11:36.167
and he seemed like he was having
a pretty good time.

11:36.167 --> 11:37.400
[LAUGHS]

11:37.400 --> 11:39.367
CHARLIE:
All right, thanks anyway.

11:39.367 --> 11:40.367
[BEEPS OFF]

11:40.367 --> 11:41.767
[SIGHS]

11:49.501 --> 11:51.567
[GRUNTS]

11:51.567 --> 11:53.200
I don't wanna see you.

11:54.934 --> 11:57.467
Look, I know you're pissed.

11:57.467 --> 11:58.934
I don't wanna hear it.

11:58.934 --> 12:00.901
And I don't care
what your excuse is.

12:00.901 --> 12:02.934
I don't have one.

12:02.934 --> 12:04.200
I screwed up, period.

12:04.200 --> 12:05.434
And I'm sorry.

12:05.434 --> 12:07.367
I'm really sorry.

12:12.534 --> 12:15.534
I just thought that I would--
I would stop by this party,

12:15.534 --> 12:18.968
and when I got there,
I kinda spaced it. And I swear,

12:18.968 --> 12:20.534
if-- If I could do it again--

12:20.534 --> 12:22.133
You can't.

12:22.133 --> 12:23.634
I know, I know.

12:23.634 --> 12:25.801
I-I know I can't.

12:25.801 --> 12:27.300
I'm a jerk. I'm an--

12:27.300 --> 12:28.667
I'm an idiot.

12:28.667 --> 12:31.434
No argument here.

12:31.434 --> 12:33.767
And what kills me

12:33.767 --> 12:36.234
is that I know how important
last night was to you,

12:36.234 --> 12:38.400
and I really wanted to help you.

12:38.400 --> 12:40.100
And I just..

12:40.100 --> 12:42.601
God, I just-- I just blew it.

12:42.601 --> 12:45.501
Well, look, Bay,
maybe you should, you know--

12:45.501 --> 12:47.267
Instead of beating yourself up
over this,

12:47.267 --> 12:49.901
maybe you should just
learn from it.

12:49.901 --> 12:52.601
You know? Think of it as a--
As a wake-up call.

12:52.601 --> 12:56.300
Well, that's what it is,
man, bigtime.

12:56.300 --> 12:58.501
I'm awake.

12:59.701 --> 13:01.100
[SIGHS]

13:01.100 --> 13:03.000
Drink this.
[GLASS CLINKING]

13:03.000 --> 13:04.501
You look like hell.

13:09.734 --> 13:11.901
I swear, if I say "stop"

13:11.901 --> 13:14.634
he'll automatically say "go"
just to disagree with me.

13:14.634 --> 13:15.901
What do you want me to say?

13:15.901 --> 13:17.701
You know how I feel about him.
You're on my--

13:17.701 --> 13:19.501
Then he lets Grace
in on the conversation

13:19.501 --> 13:21.100
like she's some member
of the family,

13:21.100 --> 13:23.067
like she gets a vote.

13:23.067 --> 13:24.367
Yeah? What'd she say?

13:24.367 --> 13:27.567
She said it would be illegal
for us to travel together.

13:27.567 --> 13:28.934
Illegal.
Can you believe that?

13:28.934 --> 13:30.734
She doesn't even know
when my birthday is.

13:30.734 --> 13:33.601
You gotta admit, if there's one
thing those people know about,

13:33.601 --> 13:36.234
it's the ins and outs
of the legal system.

13:38.934 --> 13:40.100
What?

13:41.767 --> 13:43.033
You ready to go?

13:43.033 --> 13:44.234
I'm gonna be late.

13:45.467 --> 13:47.701
Uh, okay.

13:47.701 --> 13:49.033
Yeah, sure.

13:52.734 --> 13:55.534
Is this some sort of clown joke
or something?

13:55.534 --> 13:57.434
What could you possibly do
in two hours

13:57.434 --> 13:58.901
that's worth 250 bucks?

13:58.901 --> 14:00.300
Plenty. I juggle.

14:00.300 --> 14:03.334
I do magic tricks,
balloon animals.

14:03.334 --> 14:05.100
Oh, new friend?

14:05.100 --> 14:06.767
Callie, Coco.
Coco, Callie.

14:06.767 --> 14:07.934
How you doing?
[SIGHS]

14:07.934 --> 14:09.701
Okay, what if we
bag the balloon animals?

14:09.701 --> 14:11.801
What does that save us?
Twenty-five bucks.

14:11.801 --> 14:14.434
Well, then what if we
go without magic tricks?

14:14.434 --> 14:16.267
Bad idea.
The kids like the magic.

14:16.267 --> 14:18.000
Okay, but what if?

14:18.000 --> 14:19.367
Another 25, I guess.

14:19.367 --> 14:20.701
That's not good enough.

14:20.701 --> 14:23.767
Look, I'm a businessman,
and I got another job to get to.

14:23.767 --> 14:26.801
Come on, Coco,
work with me here.

14:26.801 --> 14:29.133
I got 80 bucks.

14:29.133 --> 14:30.934
Eighty bucks?

14:30.934 --> 14:34.467
For 80 bucks you can go rent
your own damn clown suit.

14:34.467 --> 14:36.167
I gotta go.

14:36.167 --> 14:37.467
[SIGHS]

14:38.734 --> 14:41.267
Now, that was a pitiful display.

14:41.267 --> 14:43.534
What? I'm in a bind here.

14:43.534 --> 14:44.934
Isn't this, like, a family
thing?

14:44.934 --> 14:46.567
Why can't they
just give you money?

14:46.567 --> 14:49.634
They did. Remember that round
I bought at the bar last night

14:49.634 --> 14:51.133
for, like, 12 people?

14:51.133 --> 14:53.601
You bought a round with
your brother's clown money?

14:53.601 --> 14:56.200
Hey, how was I supposed to know
clowns were so expensive?

14:58.067 --> 15:01.133
Yeah, I need a clown
for under 80 bucks. Talk to me.

15:01.133 --> 15:02.467
[JULIA SIGHS]

15:02.467 --> 15:04.667
"Those people."

15:04.667 --> 15:07.033
He actually said
"those people."

15:07.033 --> 15:09.834
Well, wait. I mean,
how exactly did he say it?

15:09.834 --> 15:11.467
I was complaining
about Grace saying

15:11.467 --> 15:12.834
that our trip
might be illegal.

15:12.834 --> 15:14.634
And he said something like,

15:14.634 --> 15:17.400
"Those people know a lot about
the legal system."

15:17.400 --> 15:19.067
Those people mean blacks,
right?

15:19.067 --> 15:22.067
Like, a blacks
and crime thing?

15:22.067 --> 15:24.334
Well, no, not necessarily.

15:24.334 --> 15:26.133
You know, maybe--
Maybe he meant, like--

15:26.133 --> 15:27.467
Like homeless advocates.

15:27.467 --> 15:29.200
You know, people who do
her kind of work.

15:29.200 --> 15:31.400
I don't think so. He was
snickering like it was a joke.

15:31.400 --> 15:33.367
People don't joke about
homeless advocates.

15:33.367 --> 15:35.067
WOMAN:
There you are.

15:35.067 --> 15:36.934
"Happy anniversary,
Leo and Ted?"

15:37.601 --> 15:38.634
Not you?

15:38.634 --> 15:40.734
Try "Happy birthday, Owen."

15:41.801 --> 15:43.467
Owen, okay.

15:43.467 --> 15:44.567
 You know, I-I just think

15:44.567 --> 15:47.133
there's gotta be
another explanation.

15:47.133 --> 15:48.968
Well, I'll tell you what.

15:48.968 --> 15:51.033
When you come up with it,
you let me know.

15:52.334 --> 15:53.801
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

15:55.100 --> 15:56.501
Thanks.

15:56.501 --> 15:58.701
I'm carrying like 40 pounds
of sugar and lard here.

15:58.701 --> 15:59.634
[GRUNTS]

16:01.234 --> 16:03.834
Where you going? I thought we
were cleaning the yard together?

16:03.834 --> 16:05.534
[DOORBELL RINGS]
Yeah, like I'm dying

16:05.534 --> 16:08.367
to listen to you guys
fight more.

16:11.801 --> 16:13.901
Oh, we already have a religion,
thank you.

16:13.901 --> 16:16.234
Oh, no, no.
[CHUCKLES]

16:16.234 --> 16:17.334
We're, um--

16:17.334 --> 16:20.801
Mom, Dad, what are you
doing here?

16:20.801 --> 16:22.467
We came to see
where you live, honey.

16:22.467 --> 16:24.334
Okay.

16:24.334 --> 16:26.801
Well, this is it.

16:26.801 --> 16:28.934
And, yes,
it's always this messy.

16:29.801 --> 16:31.167
This is a beautiful house.

16:31.167 --> 16:32.667
Spare me the niceties, Dad.

16:32.667 --> 16:34.734
Just cut to the chase.
I'm making a huge mistake.

16:34.734 --> 16:36.868
This one's as bad
as all the others. Blah, blah.

16:36.868 --> 16:38.667
You know what?
I don't care what you think.

16:38.667 --> 16:40.634
Grace, honey, relax.

16:40.634 --> 16:42.000
We like Charlie.

16:42.000 --> 16:44.367
He seems
like a great guy.

16:44.367 --> 16:47.000
But even more important,
you look great.

16:47.000 --> 16:49.901
Like you finally realized
you don't have to suffer

16:49.901 --> 16:51.000
to be happy.

16:51.000 --> 16:52.000
CHARLIE:
Grace!

16:52.000 --> 16:54.334
Have you seen my--? Oh.

16:54.334 --> 16:55.334
ROSE:
Hi.

16:55.334 --> 16:56.934
Rose, Martin.

16:56.934 --> 16:59.968
My wife and I decided
to, uh, forget our manners

16:59.968 --> 17:01.567
and drop in unannounced.

17:01.567 --> 17:03.334
No problem.

17:03.334 --> 17:06.032
Um, listen, I'm sorry
about last night. It was, uh--

17:06.032 --> 17:09.000
No apologies necessary.
We have three children.

17:09.000 --> 17:10.099
We have been there.

17:10.099 --> 17:12.901
[ALL LAUGHING]

17:12.901 --> 17:16.267
Um, did Grace
show you around already?

17:16.267 --> 17:18.067
Um, no, but--

17:18.067 --> 17:20.233
Well, let me give you
the 5 cent tour.

17:20.233 --> 17:21.733
Okay.
CHARLIE: It's kinda messy.

17:21.733 --> 17:24.800
Hey, at least there aren't
any bullet holes in the door

17:24.800 --> 17:26.501
like her last place.
There weren't--

17:26.501 --> 17:28.801
ROSE:
We're glad to have her out of
that neighborhood.

17:28.801 --> 17:30.000
See?

17:30.000 --> 17:32.434
I'm not the only one.

17:32.434 --> 17:34.968
This is the living room.
MARTIN: It's nice, huh?

17:42.167 --> 17:44.667
So, what needs doing
out here?

17:44.667 --> 17:46.667
You could mow the lawn.

17:46.667 --> 17:49.467
Hey, Julia,
hang on a second.

17:49.467 --> 17:51.901
I gotta ask you something.

17:51.901 --> 17:54.234
I'm going nuts
with this clown thing.

17:54.234 --> 17:57.501
Turns out they're way more
expensive than Charlie thought.

17:57.501 --> 17:59.701
How stupid do you think I am?

17:59.701 --> 18:00.767
What?

18:00.767 --> 18:04.167
I already loaned you 50 bucks.
Remember?

18:04.167 --> 18:06.734
And tried to help you get a job
and you completely blew it.

18:06.734 --> 18:09.100
So if you think you can just
waltz in here scot-free and--

18:09.100 --> 18:11.467
Whoa, whoa, whoa. Now,
hold it, hold it, hang on.

18:11.467 --> 18:13.501
I don't.

18:13.501 --> 18:17.868
Look, I know how I handled
the Sam job thing was...

18:17.868 --> 18:19.000
bad.

18:19.000 --> 18:20.167
It's just
that he came at me

18:20.167 --> 18:22.067
with all these crazy
accusations,

18:22.067 --> 18:25.300
but-- But I know, I handled it
wrong. So I'm sorry.

18:25.300 --> 18:27.167
You should be.

18:27.167 --> 18:29.767
And the truth is I've handled
a lot of stuff wrong lately.

18:29.767 --> 18:33.033
I've just been--
Well, you and Sarah were right.

18:33.033 --> 18:35.267
I've been kinda out of control.

18:36.601 --> 18:38.100
Really?

18:38.100 --> 18:39.734
You--? You think that?
'Cause--

18:39.734 --> 18:41.000
I know. I know.

18:41.000 --> 18:43.167
I was really defensive
when you guys brought it up,

18:43.167 --> 18:45.234
but I've been
thinking about it, and--

18:45.234 --> 18:48.901
And yeah.
Yeah, way too much partying.

18:48.901 --> 18:52.567
So I'm gonna
pull myself together

18:52.567 --> 18:54.567
and not drink for a while.

18:54.567 --> 18:58.400
'Cause-- 'Cause I was getting
pretty sloppy there.

18:58.400 --> 18:59.934
Hm.

18:59.934 --> 19:03.868
I'm...really glad to hear
you say that, Bay,

19:03.868 --> 19:07.501
'cause it kinda felt
like you were disappearing.

19:07.501 --> 19:10.367
Well, yeah, but that's you.

19:10.367 --> 19:13.667
You do that. You take
one little bad thing

19:13.667 --> 19:15.934
and blow it up
into some major syndrome.

19:15.934 --> 19:18.300
Hm.

19:18.300 --> 19:20.801
I do do that, don't I?

19:20.801 --> 19:22.934
Get judgmental
really quickly.

19:22.934 --> 19:24.400
It's okay.

19:25.601 --> 19:27.300
Keeps you human.

19:31.400 --> 19:33.767
Hey, Bay, um,

19:33.767 --> 19:36.334
how much was it you needed?

19:36.334 --> 19:38.434
I'm not interrupting
anything, am I?

19:38.434 --> 19:40.767
No, Marcus and I were
just talking about dinner.

19:40.767 --> 19:42.067
Okay,
I know it's late notice.

19:42.067 --> 19:44.734
But, Ross, he has tickets
to a chamber music series.

19:44.734 --> 19:47.300
And he couldn't use them,
so he gave them to me.

19:47.300 --> 19:50.434
He only had two, but I called
and they still have seats.

19:50.434 --> 19:51.701
Oh, what a great idea.

19:51.701 --> 19:53.767
We can go to the concert,
then we can go to dinner.

19:53.767 --> 19:56.267
There's this cool Japanese
restaurant right by the theater

19:56.267 --> 19:58.834
where the sushi floats by you
on little boats.

19:58.834 --> 20:00.300
I know that place.
It's terrific.

20:00.300 --> 20:01.934
Marcus,
what do you think?

20:01.934 --> 20:03.567
I don't really like sushi.

20:03.567 --> 20:06.267
Oh, well, we don't
have to go there.

20:06.267 --> 20:08.567
I mean, there are plenty
of other places.

20:08.567 --> 20:09.734
No, it's okay.

20:09.734 --> 20:12.100
I don't wanna go
to the concert either.

20:12.100 --> 20:13.868
So you go.

20:13.868 --> 20:16.467
Marcus, don't be sullen.
This is a very nice offer.

20:16.467 --> 20:17.534
I'm not.

20:17.534 --> 20:19.634
I just can't go.

20:19.634 --> 20:22.434
I-I-- I told Mom
that I'd call her tonight.

20:22.434 --> 20:23.601
You go.

20:23.601 --> 20:26.434
Well, uh, wh-what'll you do
about dinner?

20:26.434 --> 20:28.334
I'm 14, Dad.

20:28.334 --> 20:29.734
I can make my own dinner.

20:29.734 --> 20:31.834
Uh...

20:33.334 --> 20:34.934
I-I'll get my coat.

20:38.501 --> 20:40.167
SAM:
The thing I said earlier?

20:40.167 --> 20:41.868
You know, I said
a lot of things earlier.

20:41.868 --> 20:43.534
You're gonna have to be
more specific.

20:43.534 --> 20:45.868
Well, I don't remember
word for word, but--

20:45.868 --> 20:48.033
This is good.
Aluminum frame.

20:48.033 --> 20:50.133
You could lug this around
for a few months, right?

20:50.133 --> 20:52.634
I-- I was whining about Grace,
and you said something like:

20:52.634 --> 20:55.434
"Those people know a lot
about the legal system."

20:55.434 --> 20:57.467
Oh, right.
Yeah, that was a joke.

20:57.467 --> 20:59.267
Here, you gotta
try it on to see.

20:59.267 --> 21:02.100
So when you said
"those people,"

21:02.100 --> 21:03.701
you meant blacks?

21:03.701 --> 21:05.100
Right.

21:05.100 --> 21:08.467
So it was a joke about
how blacks are criminals?

21:08.467 --> 21:11.434
Oh, it's not like I think
all blacks are criminals.

21:11.434 --> 21:13.534
I'm sure lots aren't.

21:13.534 --> 21:14.601
Most.

21:14.601 --> 21:16.334
Most aren't.

21:16.334 --> 21:17.968
Whatever. Most.

21:17.968 --> 21:19.968
It's a big difference.
Fine.

21:19.968 --> 21:21.934
What--? What is your point?
That I'm a racist?

21:21.934 --> 21:23.100
'Cause I'm not.

21:23.100 --> 21:26.000
I got, like, three black guys
working for me, so--

21:26.000 --> 21:28.501
Look, I'm not attacking you.
I just wanna know how you feel.

21:28.501 --> 21:30.968
'Cause for me, I don't think
that race should be an issue.

21:30.968 --> 21:32.667
You don't think
there's any difference

21:32.667 --> 21:34.501
between blacks and whites?

21:34.501 --> 21:36.200
No.

21:36.200 --> 21:38.501
So when you're driving through
the tenderloin at night

21:38.501 --> 21:39.501
and you lock your doors,

21:39.501 --> 21:41.334
what's that about?

21:41.334 --> 21:43.334
That's not because
it's a black neighborhood.

21:43.334 --> 21:45.934
It's because
it's an unsafe neighborhood.

21:45.934 --> 21:47.267
Oh, so you lock your doors

21:47.267 --> 21:50.567
in unsafe
white neighborhoods too?

21:50.567 --> 21:51.868
Hard to say, right?

21:51.868 --> 21:53.567
It's 'cause there aren't any.

21:53.567 --> 21:55.100
[SCOFFS]

21:55.100 --> 21:56.701
That is not true.

21:56.701 --> 21:58.968
And besides,
it's more complicated than that.

21:58.968 --> 22:01.067
Oh, of course it is.

22:01.067 --> 22:04.501
Look, this is a stupid thing
to fight about.

22:04.501 --> 22:07.100
I-I-- I'm sorry if the joke
made you uncomfortable.

22:07.100 --> 22:09.701
I won't make
jokes like that anymore.

22:09.701 --> 22:11.167
Okay?

22:13.434 --> 22:14.968
Hey, check it out.

22:14.968 --> 22:17.267
Daypack inserts.
We should get some of those.

22:18.701 --> 22:20.634
[SIREN WAILING IN DISTANCE]

22:26.534 --> 22:28.000
[COINS JINGLING]

22:29.200 --> 22:30.734
[COIN DROPS]

22:35.968 --> 22:37.901
[***]

